<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/8862> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #8862" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/7> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "p. 727, footnote 23" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/1355> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #1355" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Liv. 22.35.1-2; cf. 23.21.7. An Augur when a candidate for the consulship of 216. See 210, Augurs and note 6." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/1299> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #1299" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Made a vow on behalf of the state (Liv. 21.62.9-10). Was sent to Cisalpine Gaul to aid Manlius against the Boii (Liv. 21.26.2, and 39.3; cf. Polyb. 3.40.14, and 56.6; cf. App. Hann. 5). According to Liv. 21.63.15, which may belong to the dubious tradition that Flaminius entered into office in Gaul, Atilius handed over two legions to him in 217." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/1298> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #1298" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Atilius may have held either the urban or the peregrine jurisdiction. The vow which he was ordered to make on behalf of the state could have been made by any magistrate with imperium (Mommsen, Str. 1.244), but in the other instance recorded by Livy of such a vow by a Praetor it was made by the Praetor Urbanus. After annual election of four Praetors was instituted the Praetor Urbanus seldom left Rome for more than ten days (Mommsen, Str. 2.195, note 3, cf. 1.681, note 6), but during another emergency P. Furius Philus, Pr. Urb. in 216 (see 216, note I; cf. 217, note 4) was sent to Africa with the fleet. Atilius was probably the Praetor Urbanus. See the next note." .
